== Introduction ==
'''This page introduces a few ''existing'' templates''', and others can be found:
*'''To ''make'' a template or ''modify'' one''', refer to [[Editing_Wikitext/Templates_A101|Templates A101]].
*'''To search for templates ''alphabetically''''' within Wikibooks, (not Wikipedia), follow the link to the [http://en.wikibooks.org/w/index.php?title=Special:AllPages&namespace=10 '''All Templates Namespace'''].
*'''To search for templates organised by ''category''''', follow the link to [[:Category:Templates]].
*'''To search for a template by name''', for example ''dropimage'', then enter the following in the search box on the left of any Wiki page and select ''go'':
{{block|background=transparent|template:dropimage}}

Writers are encouraged to add links for useful Wikibooks templates, perhaps in tabular form within these or other sections.   


==Page Top Sections==
{{Textontop|border=3px dashed brown|1=
{{hiddenh3|Help with the Top Section; template [[template:textontop|Textontop]]}}
The writing of Wikibooks pages gives a rapid education on the need for effort-saving methods.  This becomes all the more obvious when something a little different is needed.

The format used for this top-section is made with the template, [[Template:Textontop|Textontop]].   A border has been applied to show the template's boundary, but it is optional, and would not normally be used for the usual Wikibooks colors. This  layout removes the white-space that usually exists to the right of a page's table of contents.   Notice that ''this'' text starts right at the top.

The template adds the table of contents automatically.  Options are available, and a background color can be added for other layout plans.

An example of this template's use can be seen as the top section of the page [[Bicycles/Maintenance_and_Repair/Brakes/Adjusting_brakes|Adjusting Brakes]]. 

On a passing note; it is clear that the need to express image dimensions in only pixels limits the ability to make top sections that adapt to different screen widths.   That is to say, if relative units of measure could be applied to images, there would be great improvement.     

}}
In the event that the top section is to hold images, or images ''and'' text, there are two other templates for that purpose.   Because only ''one'' table of contents can exist on a page, these other templates cannot be demonstrated on the same page as ''Textontop''.   They are:
*[[Template:Image2ontop|Image2ontop]] allows a table of contents and two images or text in place of any of the images.
*[[Template:Image3ontop|Image3ontop]] allows a table of contents and three images or text in place of any of the images.

== Page Building Blocks ==
{{Thetop|w1=34%|br=3px dashed brown|w2=33%|w3=33%|ha2=center|leader={{hiddenh3|Layout Options; template [[template:thetop|Thetop]]}}
Pages each have certain similarities.   Most of the time the text extends across the page and the colorings match the default set.   Sometimes a more complicated layout is needed, and the setting of styles every time becomes laborious.  This becomes especially tedious when there are lots of spaced elements such as tables, lists, images, and text.   This template, within the perimeter border, has both page-wide sections and panels across the page.   There are many options for each of its five parameters and configuring it is straightforward. This text is written in the leader section of the template [[Template:Thetop|Thetop]], and the other sections below include three boxes across the page and a trailer section, similar to the leader.|1=<pre><table border=1>
<caption>Caption</caption>
<tr>
  <th>Heading 1</th>
  <th>Heading 2</th>
</tr>
<tr>
  <td>A</td>
  <td>B</td>
</tr>
<tr>
  <td>[[image:crocus_4.jpg|75px]]</td>
  <td>D</td>
</tr>
</table></pre>|2=<table border=1>
<caption>Caption</caption>
<tr>
  <th>Heading 1</th>
  <th>Heading 2</th>
</tr>
<tr>
  <td>A</td>
  <td>B</td>
</tr>
<tr>
  <td>[[image:crocus_4.jpg|75px]]</td>
  <td>D</td>
</tr>
</table>|3=The sections are adjustable
*Widths can be changed to remove a section or extend another.
*Padding can be changed, and colors too.
*Font details can be changed also.
*To make an empty section, enter a non-breaking space.
|trailer=The width of this building block matches the top section template exactly.   In fact, if it is preferred, ''this'' template could be used for a top section.   By the use of such a building block, greater consistency is afforded, and the addition of background colors allows a more interesting panelled page.

Note that a template is not needed to simply apply a more interesting color to a page.   Writers and editors with this in mind need only place all of their page text within styled HTML <nowiki>''div''</nowiki> tags.   The styling of tags is covered in [[Editing_Wikitext/Class_and_Style_Notes#Figure_5:_Typical_'in-line'_block formats|Typical 'in-line' block formats]], and if necessary, an example can be found near the top of the mark-up text for this page.   

An example of the template's use can be seen throughout the page [[Editing_Wikitext/Tables|Tables]].

}}


== Hidden Contents ==
Sometimes a page gets a bit cluttered.  Much ''detailed'' information is best tucked away where it can be accessed when needed, but where it does not detract from what is being said.

For this purpose there are templates such as [[template:dropimage|Dropimage]]. The quoted example presents a neat box with a heading and a link. The link toggles; left-clicking it the first time drops the box to show the contents.  Clicking the link again closes the box.   The amount of content can be considerable.

Despite their names, both boxes also can contain text or other elements, including other templates. For Dropimage, HTML tables are preferred to Wiki ones. They are useful for making writers tools, where they can sit in the closed state in the sandbox until needed for reference.

Examples of the use of Dropimage are shown below for an image, for text and for an HTML table.   Further examples of its use can be seen throughout the [[Editing_Wikitext|Editing Wikitext]] series.
{{-}}
{{dropimage|align=center|1=Image Example|2=[[image:Crocus_4.jpg|center|250px]]<br />''A Purple Crocus''}}        
{{tablestyles}}
{{lightcolors}}
{{-}}

== Image Templates==
{{noframeleft|margin=10px|1=[[image:crocus_4.jpg|200px]]|2=Note this frame-less caption.}}
{{hiddenh3|Frameless Image Captions}}
Images cannot include captions unless the image syntax makes use of a ''frame'' or a ''thumbnail''. Borders tend also to be of a standard format and cannot ordinarily be customised. 

These limitations are overcome by using the set of templates [[Template:Noframeleft|Noframeleft]], [[Template:Noframeright|Noframeright]], [[Template:Noframecenter|Noframecenter]],  and [[Template:Noframenone|Noframenone]].  A brief inspection of their names shows that there one for each of the standard image positions.   These templates also have a number of options.

An example of the captioning is given with the image on the left, and can also be seen on the page [[Editing_Wikitext/Pictures/The_Quick_Course|The Quick Course]].
{{-}}
{{hiddenh3|Mouse-over Images}}
Users of Internet Explorer will find that the mouseover functions do not work for them. 
{{HoverImage|Big yellow.jpg|Red chrysanthemum.jpg|right|thumb|200px|Gerbera:''hover for more<br />HoverImage as a thumbnail.'' |Chrysanthemum: ''the alternative<br />HoverImage as a thumbnail.''}}
{{noframeleft|margin=10px|cwidth=200px|{{HoverImage|Big yellow.jpg|Red chrysanthemum.jpg|200px}}|Gerbera:''Hover for the  Chrysanthemum. HoverImage used within Noframeleft.''}}
Images are usually fixed on the page but there is a technique that allows ''two'' images to occupy the same space.   An example is shown on the right. When the mouse moves over the image, a different image is shown instead.   It is designed by persons more clever than me as a template. The whole thing allows the use of the standard image options, and the template is called  [[Template:HoverImage|HoverImage]].

HoverImage's first two parameters are the ''file names'' of the two images to use; the first is the default image and the second is the alternative.   There are separate caption options too; they are written in the same sequence as the image names.   The other options like ''position'',  ''size'', and ''type of border'' can be added and apply to both images at once.   The template can be used in places where a normal image syntax line is used. The code to make the hover-image on the right is just:
{{-}}
{{block|ta=left|background=ivory|<nowiki>{{HoverImage|Big yellow.jpg|Red chrysanthemum.jpg|right|thumb|200px|Gerbera:''hover for more<br />HoverImage alone as thumbnail.'' |Chrysanthemum: ''the alternative<br />HoverImage alone as thumbnail.''}}</nowiki> }}
If the template is used for images with different shapes, some improvement is achieved by setting the height exactly and by setting the base dimension as some impossibly high value; in this way both images will be set to the intended height.   Note also that the entire template can become the ''content'' of the [[Template:Dropimage|Dropimage]] template, and still works well; in this event set the image option to ''center''.

The unwanted white border in the image example is not a fault in the template but is a consequence of using images with frames on a colored page background; it is a bug. To avoid this, simply use a frame-less image.   If a caption is needed as well then use the HoverImage template as the image parameter of e.g., ''Noframeleft'', to make a frame-less image ''with'' a single caption.  The image on the ''left'' was made in this way.   The coding for mouse-hover frameless images with a single caption is just:
{{block|ta=left|background=ivory|<nowiki>{{noframeleft|margin=10px|cwidth=200px|{{HoverImage|Big yellow.jpg|Red chrysanthemum.jpg|200px}}|Gerbera:''Hover for the  Chrysanthemum. HoverImage used within Noframeleft.''}}</nowiki>}}

== Information Boxes ==
{{technote|content=This box is made with the template [[template:technote|Technote]] and is intended for use at certain points within a technical page, possibly for excessively terse points that most choose to ignore.   Since the heading can be changed also, it can take on any useful form for which the green tick-mark image is suitable.}}
{{-}}
{{caution|content=This box is made with the template [[template:caution|Caution]] and could be used in pages to focus attention on possible hazards or difficulties needing more careful attention.   It is similar in that the heading can be rephrased; thus it could also be used to indicate an error, or any form for which the red cross is appropriate.}}
{{-}}
There are many information boxes available within Wikibooks.   The majority of them find use for  administrative comments and reminders.   The background color and the text alignment are options.   As is clear from the above examples, the text can also contain hyperlinks.       
{{-}}

== Highlight Blocks ==
{{block|<nowiki>style = "background:lightyellow; color:navyblue;"</nowiki> }}
The above example shows another box, this time made with the template [[template:block|Block]] to emphasise the code lines that need to be learned for some context or another.

It uses a Courier font for programming and mark-up code descriptions.   It is intended for single lines though it will expand, and background color, font, alignment, and other elements are options.

At a more general level, the template can be used for page-building.   When one instance of the template immediately follows another, color banding becomes possible.   Since it is based on the ''div tag'' it has very few differences from the main page.

A version called [[template:blockwrap|Blockwrap]] also exists to be contained in sections of text that wrap left or right.  This was needed to overcome a bug, where ''divs'' insist on using the  full width of a page.

The template ''Block'' stacks neatly top to bottom for page-building like this:
{{block|background=beige|ta=left|<nowiki>|background=Beige|ta=left|</nowiki>}}
{{block|background=ivory|ta=left|<nowiki>|background=Ivory|ta=left|</nowiki>}}
{{block|background=mistyrose|ta=left|<nowiki>|background=mistyrose|ta=left|</nowiki>}}
{{-}}

===Banded Bullet Points===
{{container|align=center|width=80%|1=
{{dul|The usual bullets make use of the page formats as its defaults.}}
{{lul|'''''These''''' bullet points are banded and although the coloring normally extends across the entire available width, both the width and position of the container are options. }}
{{dul|They are clumsy by template standards since they need the use of the three separate templates [[template:Container|Container]], and within it a stack of [[template:Dul|Dul]], and [[template:Lul|Lul]] to make it work.}}
}}
Although this set of templates lacks elegance it has been found to save time over the more laborious method that involves a custom table.   The template call for the above example uses a custom width and position and looks like this:
{{block|background=ivory|ta=left|<nowiki>{{container|align=center|width=80%|1=</nowiki><br /><nowiki>{{dul|first point}}</nowiki><br /><nowiki>{{lul|second point}}</nowiki><br /><nowiki>{{dul|third point}}</nowiki><br /><nowiki>etc...</nowiki><br /><nowiki>}}</nowiki><br />}}

== Hidden Headings ==
As will no doubt be known, every heading in a Wiki is listed as a link in the table of contents.  

Sometimes, there is no need for a table of contents entry, but a heading is still needed.   This is one way to avoid too many levels within the contents box.  For this purpose, the set of six templates [[Template:hiddenh1|Hiddenh1]] through [[Template:hiddenh6|Hiddenh6]] has been made to imitate the heading styles.

For example, the use of   ''<nowiki>Hiddenh3</nowiki>'' corresponds to a ''level three'' heading in Wiki, and an ''h3'' heading in HTML. Use them, for example, within drop-boxes, where otherwise closed boxes might cause listing confusion.   Because they are not taken formally as listings, it will not be possible to link to such headings as would otherwise be the case.   
{{-}}


== Drop Capitals ==
{{drop|A}}drop capital is this big letter at the start of the paragraph.   It is sometimes used in art work or to start stanzas in prose, though at the most general level, it finds use where there is no formal heading style.  It is a form of text emphasis, in that it directs attention to the start of a section.

The example uses the template [[template:drop|Drop]].   It is only the first letter that is contained in the template call, and in every case, the next text character, (ignore any space), is typed hard left against the template's closing brackets.

For those who need a more complicated format of their own, it will be necessary to make one, since as far as is known, this is the only one on file.   A point worth noting is that drop capitals are unlikely to line up vertically, unless a mono-spaced font is found for the purpose.  For this reason they tend to be used far enough apart to avoid the discrepancy.    
{{-}}

==Writers' Data Lists==
While working on a page there is often some CSS code or color format that needs reference. To avoid the need for page-searching a number of templates containing such information can be placed adjacent to the work, on the page or sandbox, ready for use.   The lists are compact since they are hidden in drop-boxes until they are needed. The list so far includes these:
*[[template:Tablestyles|Tablestyles]]; ''a list of CSS styles and HTML attributes of particular use for making tables. The text also contains notes on code spacing and priorities.''
*[[template:Lightcolors|Lightcolors]]; ''a list of selected pastels and light color names, with their RGB and HEX values.''
*[[template:Mediumcolors|Mediumcolors]]; ''a list of medium density color names and their codes.''
*[[template:Darkcolors|Darkcolors]];''a list of dark colors and their codes.''
*[[template:Greycolors|Greycolors]];''a density spaced list of greys with their RGB values.''   
*[[template:flowers|Flowers]];''a gallery of high quality flower thumbnails for quick image-finding.''

</div>
